Databases and SQL

Structured Query Language (SQL - pronounced ess-que-el or sequel) - language used by relational database management systems (RDBMS)

  • Used to obtain data from tables (rectangular data sets)
  • Used to combine data from separate tables
  • Tables have 'keys' that relate them
  • Manipulate and create variables
  • Structure and edit databases

Source: https://blog.stefanproell.at/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ER.png

Databases and SQL

Lahman package contained tables with keys

  • The main form of this database is a relational database in Microsoft Access format. The design follows these general principles: Each player is assigned a unique code (playerID). All of the information in different tables relating to that player is tagged with his playerID. The playerIDs are linked to names and birthdates in the Master table. Similar links exist among other tables via analogous *ID variables.
  • The database is composed of the following main tables:
    Master
    Player names, dates of birth, death and other biographical info
    Batting
    batting statistics

Source: https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/pentaho-data-integration/9781783280674/apas05.html

Databases and SQL

Structured Query Language (SQL - pronounced ess-que-el or sequel) - language used by relational database management systems (RDBMS)

  • Database Manipulation Language (DML) - basic commands similar to our comon dplyr commands (select(), filter(), etc.)
  • Database Definition Language (DDL) - structure objects in a database (create a new table for instance)
  • Database Control Language (DCL) - administration of databases (we won't cover any of this)

Databases and SQL

Structured Query Language (SQL - pronounced ess-que-el or sequel) - language used by relational database management systems (RDBMS)

  • Many popular RDBMS, some free some proprietary (often referred to as databases…)

  • Oracle - most popular (cross platform)

  • SQL Server - Microsoft product

  • DB2 - IBM product

  • MySQL (open source) - Not as many features but popular

  • PostgreSQL (open source)

Basic language constant across all - features differ

Databases: Common flow in R

  1. Connect to the database
  • DBI package, dbConnect() function
  • 1st arg to dbConnect() is database backend (need appropriate R package)
    • RSQLite::SQLite() for RSQLite
    • RMySQL::MySQL() for RMySQL
    • RPostgreSQL::PostgreSQL() for RPostgreSQL
    • odbc::odbc() for Open Database Connectivity
    • bigrquery::bigquery() for google's bigQuery
con <- DBI::dbConnect(RMySQL::MySQL(), 
  host = "hostname.website",
  user = "username",
  password = rstudioapi::askForPassword("DB password")
)

Databases: Common flow in R

  1. Connect to the database
  • DBI package, dbConnect() function
  • 1st arg to dbConnect() is database backend (need appropriate R package)
  1. Use tbl() to reference a table in the database
  2. Query the database with SQL or dplyr/dbplyr
  • dplyr verbs will get you pretty far without needing to know SQL or dbplyr

Databases and SQL

Can use basic dplyr code to produce SQL queries

tbl(my_db, "Pitching") %>% select(ends_with("ID")) %>% 
    filter(yearID == 2010) %>% show_query()

<SQL>
SELECT *
FROM (SELECT 'playerID', 'yearID', 'teamID', 'lgID'
FROM 'Pitching')
WHERE ('yearID' = 2010.0)

Databases and SQL

How dplry works with a database

  • It never pulls data into R unless you explicitly ask for it

  • It delays doing any work until the last possible moment - it collects together everything you want to do and then sends it to the database in one step

Databases and SQL

  • dplyr does not give super 'readable' SQL code necessarily
## <SQL>
## SELECT *
## FROM (SELECT `playerID`, `yearID`, `teamID`, `lgID`
## FROM `Pitching`)
## WHERE (`yearID` = 2010.0)
tbl(my_db, sql(
"SELECT `playerID`, `yearID`, `teamID`, `lgID`
        FROM `Pitching`
WHERE (`yearID` = 2010.0)")) %>% collect()

Joins

  • May want to combine two data sets: left_join(), right_join(), inner_join(), full_join()

(Cite: http://rpubs.com/justmarkham/dplyr-tutorial-part-2)

b <- data_frame(color = c("green", "yellow", "pink"), size = c("S", "M", "L"))

Subsetting/Manipulating Data

SQL code:

inner_join(select(tbl(my_db, "Pitching"), "playerID", "yearID", "W"), 
             select(tbl(my_db, "AwardsPlayers"), "playerID", "yearID", "awardID")) %>% 
  filter(yearID > 2010) %>% show_query()
## <SQL>
## SELECT *
## FROM (SELECT `LHS`.`playerID` AS `playerID`, `LHS`.`yearID` AS `yearID`, `LHS`.`W` AS `W`, `RHS`.`awardID` AS `awardID`
## FROM (SELECT `playerID`, `yearID`, `W`
## FROM `Pitching`) AS `LHS`
## INNER JOIN (SELECT `playerID`, `yearID`, `awardID`
## FROM `AwardsPlayers`) AS `RHS`
## ON (`LHS`.`playerID` = `RHS`.`playerID` AND `LHS`.`yearID` = `RHS`.`yearID`)
## )
## WHERE (`yearID` > 2010.0)

Subsetting/Manipulating Data

tbl(my_db, sql(
"SELECT `LHS`.`playerID` AS `playerID`, `LHS`.`yearID` AS `yearID`, `LHS`.`W` AS `W`, `RHS`.`awardID` AS `awardID`  
FROM (SELECT `playerID`, `yearID`, `W`
               FROM `Pitching`) AS `LHS`
INNER JOIN (SELECT `playerID`, `yearID`, `awardID`
               FROM `AwardsPlayers`) AS `RHS`
ON (`LHS`.`playerID` = `RHS`.`playerID` AND `LHS`.`yearID` = `RHS`.`yearID`)")) %>% collect()

Overview of dplyr package cheatsheet

  • Basic commands
    • tbl_df() - convert data frame to one with better printing
    • filter() - subset rows
    • arrange() - reorder rows
    • select() - subset columns
    • mutate() - add newly created column
    • transmute() - create new variable
    • group_by() - group rows by a variable
    • summarise() - apply basic function to data
    • left_join(), right_join(), inner_join(), full_join() - commands to combine multiple data frames
